      <body>
         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">22/6/86 ¶ Annotated in purple pencil to left of date: Mr Baker |And13/8/86[letter not found]. ¶  ¶ A late evening hour is devoted to you, dear Mr Dyer, to reply early to your kind letter of yesterday ...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">86.06.22</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To William Thiselton-Dyer</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RBG Kew,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Kew Correspondence. Australia. Mueller, 1882-1890,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>ff. 175 - 180.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">22/6/86<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn0" n="1">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Annotated in purple pencil to left of date</seg>: Mr Baker |<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>And<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>13/8/86<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">[letter not found]</seg>.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>A late evening hour is devoted to you, dear Mr Dyer, to reply early to your kind letter of yesterday<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn1" n="2">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>No letters to M dated 1886 from W. Thiselton-Dyer have been found.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>arrival, so that I may be sure, not to be behind on the mail day, when the work is always particularly overwhelming.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>In first place let me record my delight, that my former sending of fern-stems proved so opportune for decorating the Victorian Court, as done by you so obligingly and so circumspectly. The Giant Todea of mine, forwarded with the Commissioners goods, ought to thrive its fronds<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">quickly</hi>
               </seg>, so as to be at once available for the purpose, it was sent for.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Had I known that Kew was not well provided with Alsophila australis, I could have sent most easily stems of it, as in many of the Ranges of Victoria, particularly in the basaltic formation it is more frequent than Dicksonia antarctica, occupying the slopes, not the margin of rivulets, as the Dicksonia does; - but the Alsophila is far less a good traveller over long distances, nor does its stem serve so well for epiphytes; hence it is not much sent out from here, unless on special demand.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>As regards the fern-question, let me assure you and Mr Baker, that also in this respect I shall be as<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">loyal</hi>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>to Kew as in other considerations; but<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">exceptional</hi>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>cases will occur sometimes, one such being Prof. Lüerssens wish to receive for his monography of pacific ferns<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn2" n="3">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                           <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                        </seg>Luerssen (1871).</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>whatever I could send in return for a<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">very</hi>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>large collection of Mrs<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Dietrich's<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn3" n="4">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>M wrote Diettrich, but appears to have deleted the second<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>'t'.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Queensland plants; Now,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>it was to a Central Institution for Researches on Australian plants of very great importance, to have one of the<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">main</hi>
               </seg>-sets of Mrs D.'s plants, as Monographers are sure on many occasions to quote the numbers, altho'<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">very few</hi>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>novelties were in the huge lot.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn4" n="5">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Amalie Dietrich's collections were sent to the Godeffroy Museum of Natural History in Hamburg, which employed her; see Sumner (1988). Godeffroy's was a trading house and sold sets of the specimens; see appendix to Lüttge(1988). The collection at MEL includes<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>several specimens of<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Acacia dietrichiana</seg>,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>described in B82.07.04, p. 149,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>collected<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>by Dietrich at<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">Lake Elphinstone</seg>, Qld.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Most Cyperaceae came not to me but went to Bökeler, the Orchids to Reichenbach and Lüersen<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn5" n="6">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Luerssen.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>(of course) kept the ferns.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>I had therefore to make a special effort for returning a<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>"quid pro quo"<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>to Prof Lüerssen, and as he most particularly desired also New Guinea ferns, I gave him also what I could spare. Still, I saw<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">little novelty</hi>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>among them, just as among D'Albertis, which I worked myself out for the<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>"Papuan plants"<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>in<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">1876</hi>
               </seg>.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn6" n="7">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Luigi Maria D'Albertis'<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>plants, including ferns (pp. 76–82), were described in B76.12.03.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Kew will have Beccaris ferns.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Prof Oliver's suggestion is a good one, to send whatever I have of N. Guin.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>fern on loan to Kew;<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">I will gladly do</hi>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>so; and Mr Baker can then retain, whatever he needs for the Kew collections, dividing the unica.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn7" n="8">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">vertical red pencil mark in the left margin next to</seg>
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>and Mr Baker . . . the unica.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Prof Lüerssen makes such slow progress with the Papuan ferns, though hardly any novelty seems among them, that I latterly named most of the ferns myself.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn8" n="9">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>B76.12.03, pp. 76-82.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>New Guinea is so interjacent to Australia and the Sunda-Islands, that not such a very large access from there can be expected in ferns,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>unless the highest reigning,<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn9" n="10">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>unless . . [rei]gning<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">interlined</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">.</seg>
                     </p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>as from an isolated place as Madagascar. Please, tell the excellent Mr Baker particularly, that nothing will give me greater pleasure, than to serve<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">him</hi>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>in his fernstudies,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>as he is likely also to add in the next edition the Lycopodiaceae and Rhizospermeae; irrespective of this, he has acted on several occasions most generously to my Department, and<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">that</hi>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>I will always bear in grateful remembrance. But there seems no great hurry, to send the N.G. ferns on loan, as the new edition<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn10" n="11">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">vertical blue pencil line in left margin next to</seg>
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>seems no great ... edition</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>of the synopsis<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn11" n="12">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Hooker &amp; Baker (1865–8).<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     </p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>seems not yet forthcoming; and I am at this moment so beset with various work, that I should like to take nothing in hand that is not absolutely necessary at once. Mr Forbes has sent no ferns, as by prearrangement they are allotted to Mr Carruthers.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn12" n="13">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>M to W. Carruthers 21 October 1885 (in this edition as 85-10-21a) had suggested that Caruthers work out the ferns in the Henry Forbes collection.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>W. Carruthers to M 1 March 1886,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>set out arrangements for the description of<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>the other groups.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I have never seen yet a<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>specimen<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>of<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Hemitelia<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Godefroyi<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn13" n="14">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Hemitelia godeffroyi?</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>nor of Asplenium Dietrichianum.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I have not seen your brother in law<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn14" n="15">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Brian Hooker.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>lately, nor had I any letters from him recently; the very fact of he not having any cause to write, I take as a testimony<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>(nevatively<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn15" n="16">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>negatively?</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>),<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>that he is all right.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>As yet little of actual novelty has turned up from New Guinea, except among Mr Forbes &amp; the Rev Mr Chalmers last plants. I will see Kew provided as far as I can, with any thing of particular interest. Mere new locality (as Papuan) for well known species, will not be of importance. Unfortunately the supply of plants from New guinea on account of the difficulty of transit in<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">such</hi>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>a country is always small, and as regards Mr Forbes<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">only set</hi>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>for Australia, it has to be divided between the institutions of the<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">three</hi>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>colonies who supported his enterprise in 1885 &amp; 1886.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn16" n="17">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>See M to W. Carruthers, 21 October 1885, in this edition as 85-10-21a.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>In adopting the book-form for<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">small</hi>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>wood-specimens as the most elegant and handy, I was always particular to keep the portion, imitating the leaf-portion,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">quite unvarnished</hi>
               </seg>; thus the texture of the wood can be splendidly<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">seen both longitudinally and transversely</hi>
               </seg>.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Of course a timber-collection and a wood collection have two different objects; and if a timber collection mainly of interest for builders is to be made, such as Mr Newbery<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>had made through Mr Barnard (a nephew of Sir James Smith) a very<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">large expenditure</hi>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>is incurred, and very<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">large</hi>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>space is needed for accommodation. A small piece of wood varnished on one side is not a pretty object, and shows no more the structure of the wood as my book-fashion does. You must have failed to notice, that a portion of each wood-book in the Vict. Court remained quite without varnish.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn17" n="18">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>In the Victorian Court of the Colonial and Indian Exhibition, London, 1886, in Class 34, M exhibited<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">'</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Products of the cultivation of Forests and of the Trades appertaining thereto</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">'</seg>,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>'(1) Four Repositories containing samples of 166 species of Australian Woods in book form (2) Three Glass Cases containing 182 Articles manufactured of different kinds of Australian Woods.'<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>In the same Class the Technological Museum ('J. Cosmo Newbery, Esq., B.Sc., C.M.G., Superintendent') exhibited<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>'(1) A court formed of the principal Victorian Timbers, comprising 200 specimens of the most valuable; named and illustrated by pictorial specimens of the fruit, leaf, and flower of each. (2) Collection of Specimens of Woods, from the Trees and Shrubs of Victoria, adapted for economic purposes. Prepared for exhibition by F. W. Barnard. (The flowers and foliage painted in the Museum by Miss M. Vale.)'. See Colonial and Indian Exhibition (1886), p.195.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I hope the Xanthorrhoea and Zamia from WA. are thriving, got by Commissioners there on my suggestion.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn18" n="19">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>In the Western Australian Court the exhibit of the<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>'Perth Local Committee'<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>included<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>'A quantity of fronds from the Zamua Palm (<seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Cycad</seg>)'<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>and<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>'A Black Boy (<seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Xanthorroea</seg>), 20 feet in height, of an exceptional<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>size'<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>(Colonial and Indian Exhibition [1886], p. 261).</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The Adelaide-Exhibition<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn19" n="20">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Adelaide Jubilee International Exhibition, 1887.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>is likely to be again a severe tax, both on my time and the slender resources of my Department; still, as these Exhibitions diffuse so much practical knowledge, we must all do the best, we can, for them.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>With the wish to be kindly remembered to Sir Joseph and with best expressions of regard to yourself</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Ferd. von Mueller</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Kindly write,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">when</hi>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>I am to send off the ferns on loan.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn20" n="21">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">vertical blue line in left margin next to</seg>
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Kindly ... loan</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>I hope also soon to resume the selecting of Australian Novelties for Kew; but really the<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">local</hi>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>demands on my Department in such a varied way press heavily upon me in this<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">pushing</hi>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>colony.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn21" n="22">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Annotated below the first post-script paragraph:<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     </p>
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">In an unknown hand:</seg>
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Proniflora<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     </p>
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">In J. G. Baker</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">'</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">s hand:</seg>
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Species sent are<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                           <hi rend="underline">Selaginella proniflora</hi>
                        </seg>
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Baker [proniflora underlined in red pencil and the word printed clearly above it] &amp;<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                           <hi rend="underline">Trichomanes n sp</hi>
                        </seg>
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>near vitiense &amp; muscoides, I have just been helping<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Beccari with a list of the ferns of New Guinea (published Malesia vol. III p. 30 to 55 &amp; have described from material which he sent a new genus &amp; several new species. I should be glad any time when convenient to borrow baron Von Muellers Guinea [<seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">sic</seg>] collection. | JGB.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Luerssen as<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">yet</hi>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>described<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">not one</hi>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>new fern from N. Guinea.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn22" n="23">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Luerssen . . . N. Guinea'<seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">
                           <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>written in central margin between f 177 back and f 178 front.</seg>
                     </p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
